<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n15059d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n15" href="#n15059d">N15 (VI.D.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n15all.htm#n15059d"> 59(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> question old men</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">This book is lost, but a second edition was produced about 1135, and the portion of it relating to Iceland is still extant; whilst some portions of Are&apos;s <cite>History of Norway</cite> have been included in later books. Are Torgilsson was a conscientious inquirer who did his best to discover the truth and sift out the false, <mark>by questioning old and veracious men</mark>. He endeavoured with success to clear up chronological confusion; and his brief survey of important events and his consistent chronology deserve all praise. <small> Snorri Sturluson, <a name="SSHK" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SSHK"><cite title="source">Heimskringla: the Olaf Sagas</cite></a>, (1915) xxii</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c15235d" href="c15all.htm#c15235d">VI.C.15:235(d)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
